A debounce function limits the rate at which a function can be executed, ensuring that it only runs after a specified delay period has passed since the last time it was invoked.

Here's a simple debounce implementation along with an example of how to use it:

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
    let timeoutId;
    return function(...args) {
        clearTimeout(timeoutId);
        timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
            func.apply(this, args);
        }, delay);
    };
}

// Example usage
const logResize = () => {
    console.log('Window resized!');
};

window.addEventListener('resize', debounce(logResize, 300));
```

In this example, the `logResize` function will only be called after the window has been resized and 300 milliseconds have passed since the last resize event, preventing excessive calls during continuous resizing.
